<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=103584214439286></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103584214439286><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=103584214439286>Shield bashing</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=103584214439286#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>177 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 28th 5:15 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.15]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Just an FYI post to SKs in the world of Norrath.<br><br>If you are into mathematically calculating (estimating) damage per second (DPS), then you might find this useful.<br><br>I have been informed that shield DPS, following the patch that improved shield bashing, can be calculated using the following:<br><br>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Delay = 60<br>2.  Damage = shield AC, capped at 25  (i.e. Shield of Midnight, which has a ac of 55, would still only have a damage rating of 25 for DPS purposes).<br><br>Therefore, once you get a shield of ac 25 or greater, you are wielding a 25/60 weapon in your offhand.  <br><br>Note that there is no damage bonus for an offhand weapon.  Therefore, and most importantly, with a shield ac of 25 or greater and using a nice formula for DPS (((Damage *2) +1) / (Delay / 10)), you have a weapon that has a basic DPS of 8.5.  That isnt too bad at all.  For comparison, consider that a WAR wielding a lammy in the offhand would have a basic DPS of only 10.  For the loss of 1.5 DPS, you gain interrupt and higher AC.  Interesting to me...<br><br>Therefore, the upgrade to shield damage has a very large impact to us.  Do NOT fall into the trap that many SKs do and automatically think that 2H is better than 1H.  That just isnt a true statement 100% of the time.  When you calculate the damage that the 1H weapon is doing, and add in shield damage, it becomes a very interesting trade off.<br><br>For instance, would it shock many of you to know that a mere Shard of Night and Sarnak Battle Shield will, in general and over time, outdamage a Narandi Lance (before the proc; once it procs Boil Blood, Narandi will generally be doing more damage)??  I ran the numbers; shocked the heck out of me...<br><br>However, being a good tank, is NOT all about doing damage.  Our primary job is to absorb damage.  A higher ac allows us to do just that.  Do not discard a higher ac.  If there truly is a softcap at approx 1250, and you are under 1250, then I would argue that ac is jsut as important to us as is HP.  Translation?  If you have comparable 1H and 2H weapon, Id go 1H, as it makes you a better tank, even if it decreases your DPS.<br><br>The last sentence of the previous paragraph needs further explaination.  In general, a comparable 2H weapon will, in general outdamage a 1H weapon (plus shield).  It only makes sense to.  You sacrafice ac for damage and that seems reasonable to me.  <br><br>What I am saying, however, is that far too often, SKs will just blindly accept a 2H over a 1H for higher DPS and that jsut isnt true all the time.  Further, many ignore the increased ac that comes with wielding a shield, even when they are a far cry from 1250 ac (or so).  They have made themselves worse tanks, which is their primary role in a group, and, therefore, arguably weakened the group.<br><br>The conclusion of all this is to just put some thought into what to wield.  2H MAY be a better choice for you, but look at all your options and what situation you are in.  The difference in DPS by switching to a 2H is probably NOT as big as you think and you may be better off trading out for a 1H and a shield.  If you are under 1250ish ac, the increased ac will be a very welcome addition and you also probably added the benefit of being able to interrupt spell casting mobs (large races are an exception; they get to regardless).<br><br>Luna<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
