<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10343707172665></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10343707172665><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=10343707172665>RE: Ooops</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=10343707172665#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Guru>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>122 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Oct 11th 5:29 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.96]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Greetings Verosha,<br><br>Don't feel alone, my friend.&nbsp;&nbsp;Many people have twinked a Shadow Knight then suddenly discovered that they are having real trouble playing the class.  Many of the skills a Shadow Knight must learn in order to be effective, both solo and in a group, must be practiced over and over again.  If your equipment is allowing you to simply tank mobs without learning those lessons, then you have but one choice...Bank most of the equipment.  I know it seems counter intuitive, but doing so will accomplish two things.  First, it will help you raise your defensive skill.  Second, it will teach you a lot about how to use the spells and skills that are the bread and butter of the Shadow Knight class.  How many times have you had to Shadow Step out of a fight?  How many times have you had to Fear an additional mob and hope that you can kill the first before it comes back?  Do you know when you have overpulled for the group you are with and need to stop and die in order to save your group?  Learn these lessons and you will have begun the steps necessary to become a &quot;good&quot; shadow knight.<br><br>As far as having a purpose, I have two ideas for you.  The first is to start questing.  I don't know what race you are playing, but I think most of them have newbie quest armor.  You may not need the armor, but you might need the experience of questing for the armor.  This site is a great place to find those quests, so do a little bit of homework and out of the 2000+ quests you should be able to find a few that are interesting.<br><br>Second, I am assuming that since you have been in good gear, you have not needed to group.  Start grouping as soon a possible.  Grouping not only introduces you to new people...maybe people with a lot more experience whom you can learn from...but gives you the chance to learn to be a team player.  The grouping experience is what Everquest was built to promote.  The six or seven people I play with on a regular basis have done things that amazed me, simply because we know how to play in a group well.<br><br>Now, if you can combine questing and grouping, then you have the best the game can offer.  I have felt just as proud helping someone get a particular quest item as I have completing the quest myself.<br><br>A bit of a long post.  Sorry for being long winded.  I hope you have a great experience in the land of Norrath.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Oct 11 17:13:02 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
